[_Mycoplasma bovis_ is a pathogen causing respiratory disease, otitis media [inflammation of the middle ear], arthritis, mastitis [infection of the mammary gland and udder tissue], and a variety of other diseases in cattle worldwide. It is increasingly recognized by the veterinary and livestock communities as having an important impact on the health, welfare, and productivity of dairy and beef cattle. _M. bovis_ diseases can be difficult to diagnose and control because of inconsistent disease expression and response to treatments and vaccines, and large gaps in the current understanding of the epidemiology and pathophysiology of these diseases, which tend to become chronic and do not respond well to antibiotic treatments.

Less is known about _Mycoplasma wenyonii_, an enigmatic and incompletely understood organism, while there is growing body of evidence suggesting that it may contribute to clinical signs in cattle, particularly in dairy cows, during late summer and early autumn. Arthropods and events involving blood contact are suspected to be involved in transmission. The described clinical signs include pyrexia [fever], hindlimb and/or udder oedema and prefemoral lymphadenopathy [enlarged lymph nodes].

It deserves to be investigated if a combination of both pathogens is behind the unusual severe picture reportedly observed in the dairy farm described. Could additional factors play a role?

Both agents are not intra-nationally reportable, and are not OIE-listed, thus not under internationally agreed requirements for international trade in animals. Both pathogens are not zoonotic.

Subscribers with experience in similar events are invited to share their view.

Further reading:
1. F.P. Maunsell, A.R. Woolums, D. Francoz, R.F. Rosenbusch, D.L. Step, D.J. Wilson & E.D. Janzen. _Mycoplasma bovis_ Infections in Cattle. Journal of Veterinary Internal Medicine 25(4) 772-783, 2011, http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/store/10.1111/j.1939-1676.2011.0750.x/asset/j.1939-1676.2011.0750.x.pdf?v=1&t=i01f1zu9&s=2975a7f1fa1051d9a01d96c4d24f4ab89d164f39 (subscription).
2. Ben Strugnell and Laura McAuliffe. _Mycoplasma wenyonii_ infection in cattle. In Practice 34: 146-154, 2012, http://inpractice.bmj.com/content/34/3/146.full.pdf (subscription).
- Mod.AS

